# Typesense Synonyms & Query Expansion

## Background
Typesense is a fast, typo-tolerant, in-memory search engine. This task focuses on its **collection-level Synonyms API**, which lets you define one-way and multi-way synonyms so that user queries expand to match related terms. You will stand up a Typesense server, index a small product catalog, and configure synonyms so that searches return the expected expanded results — including when the query word itself contains a typo.

## Requirements
- Download and run the **Typesense v29.0** native Linux binary (`typesense-server`) in the background, listening on port `8108`, using the API key `xyz` (exported as the `TYPESENSE_API_KEY` environment variable).
- Persist data under a data directory so the server state (collection, documents, synonyms) survives a restart.
- Create a collection named `catalog` and import every product from the provided dataset.
- Configure one one-way synonym and two multi-way synonym groups on the `catalog` collection.
- Provide a command-line tool that can search the live collection, list the configured synonyms, and delete a synonym by id.
- Searches must expand synonyms even when the query word has a small typo.

## Implementation Hints
- Use the Typesense Synonyms API at `/collections/:collection/synonyms/:id` (upsert with `PUT`, list, retrieve, delete). Synonyms are persisted to disk, so a server restarted from the same data directory keeps them.
- A one-way synonym uses a `root` word that maps to a list of `synonyms`; searching for the root returns documents containing the mapped words. A multi-way synonym is just a list of interchangeable `synonyms`.
- Important: by default Typesense does **not** resolve synonyms on typo-corrected query tokens. You must opt in via the relevant search parameter for the typo case to work.
- Project path: /home/user/typesense-synonyms
- Data directory: /home/user/typesense-synonyms/typesense-data
- Server: typesense-server v29.0 at http://localhost:8108, API key `xyz` (also available as the `TYPESENSE_API_KEY` environment variable).
- Dataset to import: /home/user/typesense-synonyms/products.jsonl (JSONLines; each line has the keys `id`, `name`, `category`, `brand`).
- Collection: name `catalog`; index at least the string field `name` for full-text search.
- Configure exactly these three synonyms, using these exact ids:
  - `smartphone-synonyms`: one-way synonym with root `smartphone` mapping to `iphone` and `galaxy`.
  - `outerwear-synonyms`: multi-way group of `blazer`, `coat`, `jacket`.
  - `footwear-synonyms`: multi-way group of `sneaker`, `shoe`, `trainer`.
- CLI entrypoint: `python3 cli.py <subcommand>` run from the project path, supporting these subcommands:
  - `search --query "<q>"`: search the `catalog` collection by the `name` field and print to stdout a single JSON object with exactly the keys `query` (the input string) and `hits` (a JSON array of the matching documents' `id` values, as strings, sorted in ascending numeric order). Both synonym expansion and typo-tolerant synonym resolution must be active.
  - `list-synonyms`: print to stdout a JSON array of the configured synonym id strings, sorted in ascending order.
  - `delete-synonym --id "<id>"`: delete the named synonym from the `catalog` collection and print to stdout a single JSON object with exactly the key `deleted` set to the deleted id string.


