# Cross-Collection JOINs with Typesense (CLI / curl)

## Background
Typesense is an in-memory, typo-tolerant search engine. Beyond plain full-text search, it can model relationships between collections using **reference fields** and resolve them at query time with its **JOINs API**. In this task you will model a classic one-to-many relationship between manufacturers and the products they make, index both collections through the HTTP API using nothing but shell tooling (`curl`), and run joined searches that embed referenced fields directly in the search hits.

A standalone Typesense server (native Linux binary) is already installed in the environment. You are responsible for starting it and driving it entirely over its HTTP API.

## Requirements
- Start the Typesense server as a native binary listening on `http://localhost:8108`, using the API key provided in the `TYPESENSE_API_KEY` environment variable (value: `xyz`). Use a local data directory so it comes up cleanly.
- Create a `manufacturers` collection and a `products` collection. `products` must declare a **reference field** that links each product to a document in `manufacturers`, so the two collections can be joined.
- Index the exact dataset described below into both collections. Manufacturers must be indexed before the products that depend on them so that referential integrity holds.
- Run a joined search over the `products` collection that pulls the manufacturer's `name` and `country` into every product hit as a nested object, and persist the raw JSON response of that search to disk.

## Dataset (index exactly this data)

`manufacturers` documents (each has `id`, `name`, `country`):
- `{"id": "m1", "name": "Acme Robotics", "country": "USA"}`
- `{"id": "m2", "name": "Globex Instruments", "country": "Germany"}`
- `{"id": "m3", "name": "Initech Devices", "country": "Japan"}`

`products` documents (each has `id`, `name`, `category`, `price`, `manufacturer_id`):
- `{"id": "p1", "name": "Widget Pro", "category": "tools", "price": 29.99, "manufacturer_id": "m1"}`
- `{"id": "p2", "name": "Widget Max", "category": "tools", "price": 49.99, "manufacturer_id": "m1"}`
- `{"id": "p3", "name": "Gizmo 3000", "category": "gadgets", "price": 99.99, "manufacturer_id": "m2"}`
- `{"id": "p4", "name": "Gizmo Mini", "category": "gadgets", "price": 19.99, "manufacturer_id": "m2"}`
- `{"id": "p5", "name": "Sprocket X", "category": "parts", "price": 5.5, "manufacturer_id": "m3"}`

## Implementation Hints
- A reference field is declared in the collection schema with the `reference` property pointing at `"<collection>.<field>"`; this is what enables the join and what enforces referential integrity (indexing a product that points at a non-existent manufacturer must be rejected by Typesense, so do not disable that check).
- Joined fields are requested at search time with the `$<collection>(...)` syntax inside `include_fields`; by default the joined fields come back as a nested object on each hit.
- Order matters: a referenced document must already exist when the referencing document is indexed.
- The bulk import endpoint accepts JSONL (one JSON document per line); wait for `/health` to report `{"ok":true}` before creating collections.
- Project path: /home/user/joins-task
